                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/cmpl-521" class="program-course-title">
              CMPL 521 Trade Regulation (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-21044" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Law (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/627">Faculty of Law</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Comparative Law              : Historical contextualization of underlying trade principles; assessment of the interface between multilateral trade dispute resolution and domestic regulatory action in distinct public policy domains; consideration of internationalization claims, harmonization claims and the implications of trade regulation for democratic theory; particular attention to the WTO, selected regional agreements and the UN.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              This course is not scheduled for the 2014-2015 academic year.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:              There are no professors associated with this course for the 2014-2015 academic year.          </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisite: CMPL 543 (Recommended)</li>
              <li>Restriction: Not open to first year students.</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
